The Prague Stock Exchange has fallen to a minute at the end of trade
After the morning sharp decline, the Prague Stock Exchange corrected losses.
Transactions in ČEZ shares have reached almost half of daily business.
The Prague Stock Exchange has been following up on its Monday fall since the beginning of Tuesday's trade, falling by almost six percent.
This time, there's a fall in stock on Wall Street.
We, too, have a market reaction to the outcome of the vote by the US House of Representatives, which has refused to support the plan to stabilise the financial sector there.
Shares falling in Asia
The dramatic fall on Tuesday saw stock exchanges in Asia, although the indices eventually erased some of the losses during the day.
The Hong Kong Hang Seng stock market wrote off almost four percent during trade, but later deleted some of the losses and reduced the decline to about 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index, which monitors Chinese stock movements on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange, has fallen by 3.8 percent, with markets closed in Shanghai.
The stock market shares in Sydney were losing more than five percent, but in the end, the losses decreased to 4.3 percent.
The market in Taiwan has fallen by 3.6 percent according to the index there.
"The timing of the US bailout is uncertain and will affect financial markets around the world," noted the head of Hong Kong's monetary office Joseph Yam.
Hong Kong, although part of China, determines its monetary policy separately, that is, without dependence on China's central bank.
Hong Kong has interest rates at the same level as the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, US legislators should quickly return to negotiations and approve the proposal for support for the financial system.
Otherwise, it is said that other countries are also at risk of being affected.
A bloodbath of American shares
On Monday, the US House of Representatives rejected the financial system support plan, for which up to $700 billion was to be spent (almost CZK 12 trillion).
So the legislators ignored President George Bush's call to support the plan.
According to Bush, the plan would address the root causes of the financial crisis and help stabilise the economy.
American stock had a bloodbath on Monday, and major stock indices have seen the biggest fall in more than 20 years.
The Dow Jones index dropped by almost seven percent and recorded a decline to a similar extent last in 1987.
The index was already down before the vote, but as soon as it became clear that the motion in the House had failed, the index was in a free fall.
Congress retreated: The US government can pump $700 billion into banks
The leaders of the US Congress and President George W. Bush's government have agreed on a broader form of financial assistance agreement for the US financial system.
It will be voted on at the beginning of next week.
US legislators have made a breakthrough in talks about approving a rescue plan in the form of a $700 billion financial assistance to the US financial system (about $12 trillion).
But it's not won yet.
The congressmen must complete some of the details of the agreement before they can publish the final form of the law and vote on it.
The financial system support plan will be discussed at the House of Representatives on Monday.
On Sunday, Reuters was told by the chairman of the Barney Frank House Banking and Financial Services Committee.
In the Senate, according to sources, there might be a vote on the plan first on Wednesday.
According to economists, the announcement that the rescue plan will be approved should be the first significant psychological factor for the recovery of financial markets.
But then there will be "sobriety" due to the complexity of mechanisms to help markets achieve in practice.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
"We have made great progress.
We have resolved our differences on what the market stabilisation package should look like, "said Democrat Nancy Pelosi to Bloomberg.
According to her, the final vote could still take place on Sunday.
Lawyers' representatives met with US Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson on Sunday to give the final form of government funds.
This should buy out non-marketable mortgage assets from financial companies that withdraw financial firms into heavy losses and threaten the stability of the whole system.
"We are on the verge of a definitive agreement on a plan that will work and must also be effective on the market.
The recovery plan still needs to be continued, but I think we're there, "said Paulson.
Signal for Asian trading
The global financial crisis is hitting stock markets that are falling sharply.
According to Nevada's Democratic Senator Harry Reid, the legislators are trying so hard to reach a definitive agreement in Congress on Sunday.
They want to reassure investors before trading in Asian financial markets, which are the first in the time zone where Congress's decision could affect Monday's trade.
However, it is not yet clear, with certainty, when both chambers of the US Congress will vote on the law, or whether the last-minute negotiations can't be caught up in any problem.
The legislators are hoping to be approved in the next few days.
However, the law still has a number of changes.
The total amount to be allocated for the assistance of the system is to be divided into two parts.
The initial $350 billion is to be available as soon as possible, as requested by President George Bush.
Congress, however, may block the release of the remaining amount if it feels that the programme is failing in its function, in a series of additional $100 billion and later the final $350 billion.
Bush appreciates the progress in the negotiations
The President may veto this decision, but Congress may overrule its veto.
But, despite these changes, the basic idea of the program, which was to raise funds to buy out bad mortgage securities, whose value has fallen because hundreds of thousands of Americans are unable to repay their mortgages, has been preserved.
"We've worked everything out.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the law on Sunday and the Senate on Monday, "stated Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
US President Bush is also satisfied with the progress in the negotiations.
His spokesman, Tony Fratto, said that Bush is satisfied with Saturday's progress and appreciates the "mutual effort to stabilise our financial markets and protect our economy."
Limitation of gold parachutes
The Chairman of the Senate Banking Committee Christopher Dodd, the head negotiator, said that the legislators had agreed on liability for the money program, the protection of taxpayers from losses, the closure of concessions, the timing of financing the plan.
The new law is also intended to limit so-called golden parachutes for the directors of the members of the programme and to set up a committee to supervise the Fund.
That should be run by the Treasury Department.
"We have worked very hard on this and we have made great progress towards an agreement that will work and will be useful for the market and for all Americans," said Paulson.
The plan also provides assistance for homeowners who have problems with their repayment.
The government should negotiate new repayments on the mortgages it buys in order to reduce the monthly cost of repayments to debtors and allow them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological assistance
According to chief economist Patria Finance David Mark, the proposed plan is a good idea, but it will be very difficult to implement it.
