The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite advanced and our operators offer virtually all services as their partners in Western Europe.
Yet we're missing something here - a virtual operator that would make the classics cheaper.
Maybe he won't be long.
We have written on Mobil.cz many times about the fact that Czech operators are one of the most expensive in Europe.
After all, the ČTI also confirmed this, which pointed out that the price of SMS is higher in our country than in the rest of the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in regulating roaming charges, there may be a paradoxical situation - SMS from abroad will be cheaper for some customers of Czech mobile operators than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there's no competition that really wants to fight.
It may sound paradoxical, but we have three mobile networks and more than 100% penetration.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to beg that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
The President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ) Pavel Dvořák, who has said several times in the past that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is probably true that the classical operator with his own network probably no longer has much chance (after all, it would probably be hard to look for frequencies).
But there is one other option - a virtual operator.
It was the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that brought significant price reductions, to which the classical operators had to respond.
Even before the pike entered, there were voices similar to those of us in the UK before Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the market.
But it turns out that the place for such operators is and can be really successful.
After all, we do not have to go too far for examples.
In February this year we informed you about the start of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just six months, this operator has managed to acquire over 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator there.
The financial group Penta, which owns U: fona, is behind Mobilking.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility to focus on a much more specific target group.
For them to function effectively, it is enough for them to have fewer customers than for a classical operator.
They do not carry relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
In the world, virtual operators are usually profiled as low-cost - they offer cheap calls and SMS, but this is often balanced by a narrower offer of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half as cheap as its competitors.
But, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, a bet on an unprecedented target group can be quite a good move.
This operator focuses specifically on men.
"Administrative men elect a Mobilking operator they like and can trust," says David Seibertz CEO Mobile Entertainment Company, operating this virtual operator.
It is hard to say if a concept similar to that of Poland could be caught by us.
Vodafone's press secretary Miroslav Čepický doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for the segment approach on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the service supply. '
In the Czech Republic, no chance, they say mobile operators
But it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual mobile operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about expanding this successful project, but the negotiations do not look very hopeful in the Czech Republic.
More likely, Mobilking will be launched in other countries of our region, "she said in a telephone interview for Mobil.cz Jana Studnicková, press secretary of the financial group Penta.
Indirectly confirmed that existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not in favour of this idea.
Rather the contrary, they try to do everything they can to prevent any potential competitor from forming.
For some time now, the GTS Novera group has not been interested in launching a virtual mobile operator, which would like to take the next step towards becoming a real competitor of O2 Telephonics in the field of corporate customers.
"We are very interested in offering our customers not only solid but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
We have repeatedly discussed this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
We have already made progress with some of them in the negotiations, "says Pavel Kaidl, the spokesperson for the group.
Maybe there's a better time.
From unofficial information, it seems that we should be looking forward to the first virtual operator perhaps by the end of the year.
For now, however, its creation is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At the moment, we do not believe that there is room on the Czech market for the creation of a full-fledged virtual operator.
The Czech market is very specific compared to other markets.
So far we have not been approached by any subject with a complex and serious project in this area, "said Vlastimil Sršt from the Press Department of O2 Telephonics in his statement for Mobil.cz.
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile's spokesperson Martina Kemrová adds in rare agreement with O2: "So far, we have not seen any viable and mutually beneficial business project on which to build further."
And he says, "It's hard for a virtual operator to show up in T-Mobile by the end of the year.
At this point, we would have to have a concrete agreement on the table in order to be able to think in this short term. "
Vodafone pays more attention to meet the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický says: "We are open to dealing with potential virtual operators, especially in the area of cost sharing and infrastructure.
This is what we consider most beneficial in terms of customers.
The main strategy of Vodafone in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for fast mobile internet. "
Responsible offices - with operators one hand
The progress of mobile operators can be easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, leading to a fall in prices and thus a fall in their profits.
So why make it easier for such a competitor to enter?
The fact that when operators are interested in something, they can pull together, is also a testament to the U: Fona.
Probably the greatest pressure towards the ČTU went at the time of the creation of U: phone from T-Mobile.
This is indicated by publicly available information from the ČTU website.
But right now U: the phone fits as an argument why not admit the virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová also pointed out: "The competitive environment of the mobile market was recently boosted by the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that the entry of another player would place high demands on him and, above all, on his services. "
However, due to this approach of mobile operators, the total lack of interest of the Czech regulatory authorities is directly striking.
This is not just about the ČTU position, which unfortunately in the Czech Republic - unlike the UK and other developed countries - does not have the power to intervene in competition.
These belong exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Competition (ÚOHS).
But he took a typical stance on the whole issue.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible after the conclusion of a contract between a mobile operator and a virtual operator to rent the necessary infrastructure.
No such contract has been concluded so far, since the offer of potential buyers was probably not sufficiently interesting for classical operators, "said Kristian Chalupa from the Department of External Relations of the ÚOHS in response to our query.
It may not surprise the representatives of operators to make such a statement.
From an office to represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, to ensure that no one takes advantage of their position on the market, that is more than a serious one.
Especially when Kristian Chalupa adds: "In foreign countries, where virtual operators normally operate, we can see that their entry into the market has contributed to a reduction in prices for mobile telephone services."
However, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the price drop is not one of the interests of the ÚOHS.
In fact, the shocking thing about the whole case is the touching combination of three mobile operators, which results from their reactions.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence is being offered entirely alone.
Like the exact same price of petrol at petrol stations, it is certainly only a result of coincidences and tough competition.
"The Office did not find any signs of anti-competitive behaviour in this matter and therefore has no reason to interfere in any way.
None of the operators is in a dominant position and therefore does not have the appropriate increased responsibility for their market behaviour.
The necessary tools for opening up the mobile market for virtual operators are likely to lack the telecommunications regulator, "said Chalupa.
Interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of the many points at issue.
There is, of course, an analysis of the relevant markets by the ČTU, according to which telecommunications is the only market in terms of competition.
Of course, in such a market, none of the Czech operators has a dominant position.
Some legal experts, however, offer a different view - the consent of the network operator is always needed to create a virtual operator.
And the mobile operator, he has a pretty logical monopoly on his network.
So in a particular segment, it necessarily has to be dominant.
However, even if we did not accept this argument, it should be at least a warning to the OHS that three mobile operators are progressing in a striking manner.
Meanwhile, complaints from a number of interested parties (including GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles when dealing with all operators.
The imposition of liability on the Czech Technical Service is then a relatively common trick in telecommunications, by which the OHS gives its hands away from the whole matter.
We've met him in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, in the recently adopted amendment to the Telecommunications Act, the extension of the ČTU's powers to competition in telecommunications was not successful, although many experts promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the Authority must know this more than well, but apparently their interests are elsewhere.
It's okay when no one's looking.
The operation of pseudovirtual operators, of which there are several in Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
They are companies that issue their own mobile phone service price lists, but they are only partially public.
They are usually multi-level marketing companies.
For example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile telephone services.
These companies' price lists usually only reach the chosen ones.
The magic is that the company acts as a classic company customer who orders a large number of SIM cards against the operator.
As an important customer then gets special price (and more) offers.
The problem is that the trading conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar resales.
"If there were cases that you are referring to, there could be a breach of the terms of the contract that we would be dealing with and could result in an end to cooperation with the company," said Martina Kemrova on this issue.
However, it is quite unlikely that such action would be brought to the responsible people of mobile operators.
In particular, in the case of the three mentioned companies, it may be thousands of customers.
None of the operators is prevented from doing so.
In fact, these companies are making considerable profits, and, unlike real virtual operators, they do not threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický points out possible problems: "The law of similar speculation allows, however, the services of these companies are only used by a negligible percentage of customers.
In addition, they must accept that the SIM card on their phone is not in their name, so they cannot have it fully as normal customers of mobile operators. "
That, however, should be at least odd.
In addition, another question is being raised for the ÚOHS.
If mobile operators turn a blind eye to a similar process, why are they blocking the creation of a virtual operator?
It must be added that the ÚOHS has relatively strong powers to detect similar activities, and if it does not want to, it does not have to be satisfied with the explanation of operators that they have no knowledge of this and their trading conditions prohibit it.
When we won't be the most expensive
As has been said several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators to the mobile market has brought a noticeable fall in prices for services.
In fact, in virtually all countries where virtual operators were created, classical operators tried to defend their creation more or less.
The arguments used were virtually identical - too small or too saturated a market, problems with quality of services, etc.
In developed countries, however, it was at these times that regulators, which defended not the interests of mobile operators but their customers, intervened.
Whether by formal measures or informal pressure, they then achieved that the first virtual operator was created and others were packed on it.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory authorities are throwing the whole case around like a hot potato.
From our experience, we can't help but think that the ambiguity in these cases is more than appropriate.
But let's not throw the flint into the rye.
If the back-up information is correct and the virtual operator is really soon to appear, the Czech mobile market may be moving again.
If one of the operators has admitted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, it will hardly be possible for the OHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And maybe we'll stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
