Prague public transport on Wednesday for the first time even on the chip
Wednesday, October 1, 2008, will be entered in the history of the Prague Transport Company as the date when the first passengers will board the metro, tram and bus, who will have an electronic coupon in their pocket instead of a paper ticket.
At this point, he can get about 100,000 people who own the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can purchase a 30-day, 90-day and annual coupon (which will apply from 1 January 2009) while recording their chip card in the traffic business's infoculars and workplaces at the metro stations Muzeum, Bridge, Holešovice Station, Angel, Roztyla, Letňany, Kobylisa, Garden of Eden, Kacherov and Luka.
Buyers can also be purchased via the Internet on the website of the Transport Company www.dpp.cz. since yesterday
Over 400 customers have used the service by afternoon hours.
Those who start using the online store can definitely forget about the window of the metro stations, where they still had to stand regularly in long queues for paper tickets.
They buy the coupon online, and they upload it to the Opencard card in one of the 13 branches of the City Library.
"In these places passengers are provided with a counter with trained service, which will help interested people with online purchase and also upload a purchased coupon to their card," said Martin Petrný, the spokesperson for the project.
In addition to libraries it will be possible to record electronic coupons on Opencard also in self-service vending machines, which are mounted in several vestibule metro.
What do vending machines look like?
They are red, resembling ticket markers, and passengers may have already noticed them at Roztyly, Budejovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská metro stations.
"Now there are five in the city, but by the end of the year there should be eighty," added the Caretaker.
The coupon checks the driver's seat of the automatic
The service of the vending machines that will start working tomorrow is simple.
Just insert the Opencard chip card into it and the previously paid coupon will upload itself to it.
From tomorrow, electronic coupons are valid not only in the capital, but also in its surroundings.
Thus, in suburban trains and bus lines with numbers 300 to 499, mainly the inhabitants of the Central Bohemian municipalities go to the capital.
"On trains included in Prague Integrated Transport, the conductor is equipped with card readers to determine the time and band validity of coupons," explained Filip Drápal's ticket check from the Ropid organisation, which compiles timetables for Prague public transport.
The suburban buses have card readers built into the driver's cash register.
So not only does the chip card have to be shown to the driver, but also it is necessary to attach Opencard to the designated place on the side of the ticket counter.
This will check the validity of the uploaded coupons.
"If a passenger needs to verify the validity of recorded coupons, there is nothing easier than asking the driver for this information," added Drápal.
Passengers who do not ride suburban buses and will not remember when the coupon expires may go back to self-service vending machines where the card coupons are recorded.
Here, information on the validity of their documents will be displayed on the instrument display.
Sudets wanted a referendum from the US
In 1945, the Sudeten Germans asked for the inclusion of Shumava with the United States.
It comes from a letter that is stored in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want to live, at least, under the patronage of the United States of America.
With such a wish, some groups of Sudeten Germans allegedly turned to the President of the United States in 1945.
This follows, among other things, from a letter which has been preserved in a private archive and is today stored in collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
The Germans from Český Krumlov ask in a letter to the US President not to allow the return of the "Šumava County" - taken by Hitler on the basis of the Munich Agreement - back to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation correctly, and we want to be really sure that US troops are coming to German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," it is written in a letter signed in the words "People to whom the fate of Shumava lies at heart."
Since joining Czechoslovakia allegedly gives Sudeten Germans - with knowledge of the Czech national nature - hope only for brutality, indiscretions, oppression and slavery, the authors of the US President's letter to take over the protectorate for both present and eternal times.
