The pride and obstacles of the life of black people in a separate city
Hidden among the larger Orlando theme parks, a few miles from anything shiny, noisy and giant, lies a quiet city in which pride and the difficulty of African-American life comes to life.
Eatonville, the first completely black city, which was incorporated into the state and where Zora Neale Hurston spent her childhood, is no longer as simple as described in 1935: "the city of five lakes, three croquet courses, three hundred brown skins, three hundred good swimmers, plenty of quava, two schools and no prison."
Now it's a pilgrimage place.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to the annual Eatonville Zora Festival to pay tribute to Hurston, the most famous female writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
The city she described remains on the sidelines, even though she made it a tourist stop by including it in the Florida tourist guide created by the Federal Writers project from the time of the economic crisis.
It's still as independent, dignified and private as it was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted and shared their true feelings with a white man who "knows so little about us that he doesn't even know what he's missing."
Even today, in a year when a black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, calls for an open debate on races, many residents remain cautious about foreign views.
"We pay close attention to how our story is told," says 59-year-old Hortense Jones, who has lived here since birth and is a member of the oldest parish in the city.
"It has to be right."
Eatonville has long been characterized as a paradox of triumph and exertion.
It is both a historical model of the black rise and a community of almost 2400 people, where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is a centre of literature, but also an oak tree shielded by an example of Southern rural black culture - sometimes despised, sometimes praised - that came from American slavery.
It is not surprising that the residents here are both proud and protective.
And the concern about the idea of Eatonville really started with Zora, which is the only way Hurston is called here.
She introduced her hometown to the world through heartfelt books full of dialects like "Mules and Men (1935)" and "Their Eyes Were Watching God (1937)."
The five paragraphs of the Florida tourist guide have turned the city into road 17, which leads through the often passing center of Florida, the stage of black history and human drama.
With the thrust of the big drum in life and literature, Hurston introduced readers into the store of the first Eatonville mayor Joe Clark, and then turned to more personal places.
"On the left next to the road," she wrote, "is a white brown decorated modern national school with well-maintained yards and playgrounds that Howard Miller always cares about, even though he can't read or write much."
She also mentioned the new husband of the widow Dash, and she wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of all kinds and anything that fits into an hourly hotel."
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston linked Eatonville to the self-government, but also illiteracy, re-marriage and sex.
This clearly wasn't a typical publishing house, Fodor's.
It wasn't really a portrait that everyone would appreciate.
"Zora said it as it was," says the 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of Johnson's girls, who made Hurston immortal by quoting men who sang dirty songs about their beauty.
"Some people didn't like it," she added.
Hurston is still remembered here as a spry eccentric, which she often returned to after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Seventy-seven-year-old Augustus Franklin remembers that most of the time, when she came into town, she arrived unannounced in a huge Chevy, smoking and wearing pants in a city that is still proud of decent dressing.
Most of the residents were fascinated, said Franklin, but many were smirking.
"People always liked to see Zor," Franklin said.
But, he added, swinging on a chair on the back terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, "never stayed too long."
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were removed from the press.
Eatonville seemed to have forgotten her along with the rest of the world.
Although she was once a literary star, the contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she had previously lived.
There were no bigger funeral ceremonies or big public readings in Eatonville.
"I don't think they understood the importance of the world or its legacy at all," said Valerie Boyd, the author of the Hurston biography "Wrap in Rainbow" published in 2003.
The change came in the '80s.
Orange County County officials wanted to stretch the city through a five-lane highway instead of Kennedy Boulevard, which is a local two-lane main road.
Orlando's spillage has already pushed interstate highway 4 through the west edge of the city.
The proposal came at a time when Eatonville was still coming from a difficult historical period.
Forced integration, along with other things, has ended the relatively idyllic isolation of this community.
In the 1950s, the struggle to mix races brought hatred to the threshold of the community.
"At that time, a bunch of white boys, they came and threw oranges and stuff at the people who were sitting on the side," Franklin said.
"Actually, we had a lady who was killed.
They threw a melon out of the car. "
In a letter from The Orlando Sentinel in 1955, Hurston questioned the request of the Supreme Court for forced integration and declared his decision in the Brown case against the Chamber of Education that "it is offensive to my race rather than celebrating."
The population now claims that the desegregation of schools, even though it was positive in some areas, has reduced cohesion in Eatonville and undermined the courage of the young people here.
"Black children were used to hugs - I remember - you hugged your teacher in the morning, you hugged your teacher in the evening," said N. Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins and executive director of the non-profit group Preserve the Eatonville Community.
This lasted until teachers and pupils came from the same place, added.
"You're not hugging your white teacher because your white teacher - I mean, there's a cultural barrier," said Miss Nathiri.
Civil rights, however, have helped to create space for many other Zora Neale Hurston - black writers, actors and artists who, like her, have risen above prejudices with reckless self-esteem and quotes such as "How can someone deny the pleasure of my presence!
I don't understand. "
In 1975, Alice Walker made her way to Hurston's unmarked grave and began to fight to revitalize her reputation.
Five years later, Hurston's praised biography of Robert E. Hemenway, who re-classified it in the American canon, came to the shelves in bookstores.
The freeway project arrived just as the most famous daughter of Eatonville found the lights of the ramp again.
The former neighbors of Hurston now considered her a savior.
To show what could happen to its motorway, the community began planning the Hurston Festival in 1988.
Thousands of fans arrived at the inaugural event two years later, and every January many come back to celebrate.
After a few years, the state has retreated from the highway design.
"The five currents of the highway were resurrected, you would say it had detonated directly, a genuine civic pride," said Nathiri.
Boyd said it more easily, "Zora saved Eatonville."
Winning a highway project helped change the city's image.
Extraurban people like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who started going to the church in 1993, started showing up in larger numbers, and the residents started rethinking the past.
Eatonville joined the national historical registry in 1998.
The new one-story library (named after Hurston, of course) was opened in 2006 on the re-asphalted and beautiful Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains a Florida anomaly: just six miles from downtown Orlando can sometimes act as a backwater alley in the summer rain, as small as when it was founded with just 27 black families in the 1880s.
(Today it's 90 percent black.)
Strangers who come to search for the story and meaning of Eatonville are still often treated with caution.
The permission for most interviews must be given in advance and certain things - such as wall paintings in the oldest Eatonville church painted by white people and depicting black people in the fields - must not be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Jones, a brave, confident teacher who likes deep red, are still afraid that their isolated community will not be properly understood.
And even as the Hurston Festival got bigger, domestic pride also increased.
Especially young people tend to see Eatonville as Hurston saw her entire race: beautiful, with problems and so on, but not better, not worse, and as proud, creative, hardworking, foolish and diverse as other American races and ethnics.
From the voice of Franklin's nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, a sincere love for the community sounds when he plans to return to Eatonville after college to work in a local government or police department that he says would use some help.
And even younger, like the 11-year-old twins from Winter Park Alondra and Alexia Kenon, they seem to have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"Most people, when they just pass through here, think," Hm, this town is nothing against the others, "said Alondra Kenon recently after church on Sunday.
"But if you really stop and look at history for a while, it's a very nice city."
