Interview - Blood, which is again certain
Yesterday, Hema-Québec celebrated the tenth anniversary of his foundation, and his president, Dr. Francine Décary, was rightly pleased because Héma-Québec became one of the most reliable and effective blood suppliers in the world.
First of all, he regained public confidence, which was seriously shaken after the contaminated blood scandal in the '80s and' 90s.
As is widely known, the National Blood Reserve administered by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusions Department was contaminated by the HIV and hepatitis C virus during the 1980's.
In February 1994, in view of this drama and the wave of indifference to the public, the Canadian Government launched a public investigation, chaired by Judge Horace Krever, to explain the circumstances that led to such a tragedy, and to formulate recommendations that such a disaster should not be repeated.
While Judge Krever was stalling to submit a report, some provinces have set in motion a committee aimed at planning a new system of blood management in Canada.
In Québek, the Gélinea Committee held this role.
Following the Gélineau and the Krever report, two suppliers were set up in Canada: Héma-Québec, which was to be managed by Québec, and the Canadian Blood Society for the supply of all provinces and both territories.
"When Héma-Québec started his activities in 1998, hardly 38% of people still had faith in the Quebec blood system," says Dr. Décary.
"The situation was depressing.
With consistent efforts to increase the safety of blood products and permanent work in this area over the years to come, we have gained public confidence again, "he says and proudly adds that almost 94% of the Québec population had trusted Héma-Québek in early 2008.
However, Dr. Décary does not lose sight of the fact that "trust is something very fragile."
Since its founding on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the principle of prudence.
"At that time, we saw many cases in Europe of the human form of mad cow disease, a new variant of a disease called Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease," says the woman who has been leading the company since its founding in 1998.
"And we had no idea if this disease could spread with blood.
We therefore relied on one of the basic recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau report that, if we do not know this and if the spread of a serious disease is at stake, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease, which is characterised by degeneration of the brain inevitably leading to death, an exclusion measure must be taken.
Thus, in April 1999, we rejected blood from people who have been in the United Kingdom since 1980 for more than one month.
A few years ago, this disease was safely proven to be transmitted through blood.
So this episode showed us that it made sense to stick to the principle of prudence. "
In 1999, a much more accurate technique appeared on the market to detect HIV: tests using nucleic acid (NAT), which allow the detection of the presence of the virus itself in donor blood and not the presence of antibodies on which the tests used previously were based.
The NAT tests have allowed a shortening of the deaf period between the moment of infection and the moment when the first viruses in our blood can be detected, explains the specialist.
We have managed to shorten this period to less than a week.
In doing so, we have substantially reduced the risk that some donors might be infected without knowing about it and without finding out.
These improvements have enabled a significant reduction in the risk of getting AIDS through blood transfusion.
One person in 12 million is exposed today to the risk of getting HIV-contaminated blood.
"In other words, it means that 12 million blood products will need to be distributed before someone gets infected with HIV.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products every year, it will take 24 years for the first case of transmission of HIV through the blood product to occur.
I believe that today we can get or prescribe the blood transfusion necessary to heal, "says the head of Héma-Québek.
"The challenge for the next decade is to preserve the safety of our products.
We never know what kind of morbid element could appear in the system.
Just last year, a Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted to the blood by a sting of insects.
It is important to be vigilant at all times, 'Dr Décary continues and stresses that, in addition to safe supply, Héma-Québec must also expect sufficient supply.
"Needs are growing because the population is getting older.
As a result of more aggressive cancer treatment, patients often need a new dose of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing population also has consequences for the blood donor network, which on average consists of only 3% of Québecans allowed to donate. "
Any healthy person aged at least 18 years, corresponding to the criteria of admissibility, but can donate blood only once every 56 days, that is, six times a year.
14% of people offering blood are not accepted on average because they are, for example, carriers of AIDS or malaria, and if they have visited a country where there are mud chills, they are excluded for one year.
"With these 3%, we can maintain a condition that matches the needs of hospitals.
Weaknesses are very rare.
However, donor members should be supplemented in proportion to how old they are and no longer able to donate blood.
But convincing people to give blood is difficult, especially to keep them and encourage them to become regular donors.
Life is so unfettered today, we rarely find an hour to donate blood, "Francine Décary gets laid.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissue, such as bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs and skin, which is almost exclusively used for major burns.
These tissues are analysed, processed and frozen before being deposited with Hema-Québek, which also manages a single public bank of blood from the umbilical cord in Québek.
The umbilical cord, which was previously considered biomedical waste, has blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"A few weeks ago, we celebrated the deposit of our thousand blood samples from the umbilical cord into the bank, and we expect to collect over a thousand of them a year.
At the beginning of next year, we should start offering them for transplants, "says Dr. Décary, who describes the cord blood collection program as very popular.
"Some mothers are disappointed that they do not have access to it," because Héma-Quebec does not have the resources to offer this comprehensive and expensive program to all hospitals in Québek.
