In a September 17 edition, Le Devoir printed a letter from Patrick J. Garver, the executive vice president of the Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
With Orwellian logic, it confirms that the world's largest gold manufacturer has initiated the prosecution of three authors and a poor little publishing house for libel in order to create a "transparent public debate" and is demanding six million of them.
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, they do not judge truthfulness, especially in the case of prosecution for libel, but the law.
It is no surprise that Garver completely ignores this crucial distinction.
Or is it the best way for Barrick Gold to have a public debate, to bring down anyone who dares to defend the opposite position?
Whatever the outcome, the authors and publishers of Noir Canada (Black Canada) will be forced to spend respectable sums to be prepared to defend themselves and to fight in a highly unbalanced fight with an army of lawyers backed by almost bottomless pockets of the mining company.
Indeed, the tactic in these unbalanced struggles often lies in the destruction of the defendants in order to enforce a conciliation procedure that will clog the other party's mouth and, moreover, scare anyone who dares to pursue this matter.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it should have presented its views to the public.
Contrary to what is happening in several countries where Barrick Gold operates, in Canada, the debate normally lies in the exchange of ideas and not in the wounds of the baton.
So mining companies were not enough to open their books, their documentation, and to establish a real debate through newspapers, media, publications and funding of independent scientific teams that could shed light on the whole thing.
Barrick Gold, however, does not seem to have confidence in public opinion and has refused petitions and letters to support the authors of Noir Canada.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he can demand a "public debate" and at the same time despise the views of the same public?
It seems that this word in the Vice-President's world refers only to fat-paid lawyers, and not to all Canadians; that is a rather narrow concept of this concept.
In a democracy, even the oppressors have the right to speak.
