Operation to save Wall Street - Democrats and Republicans understand each other
The Bush administration and the leaders of Congress, both Republicans and Democrats, eventually reached an agreement yesterday on the largest economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
A new version of the plan to slow down the financial crisis that has been looming Wall Street for months has yet to be approved by both chambers of Congress.
In particular, it envisages: better control of the elected representatives over its application, new mechanisms to ensure the payment of public money, new measures to capture the amount of houses seized due to non-payment, and the right to monitor the level of wages paid to managers of rescued firms.
US Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, Chairman of the House of Representatives Nancy Pelosi, and Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced this good news yesterday minutes after midnight, after the two-day negotiating marathon.
"We have made great progress and reached an agreement that will be effective in the markets," said the Bush administration's representative, Henry Paulson.
"Everything has been done so that the real economy and ordinary Americans are safe from the crisis currently taking place on Wall Street," explained the democrat.
"This is a crucial point: if we do not do this, the trauma, chaos and disruption of American daily life will be huge," said the Republican Judd Gregg.
Over the last few hours, the negotiations have run to the maximum in fear of the effect of another investor default.
The designated time limit was the opening of the markets this morning.
Both candidates for the US President were invited to the negotiations later, and they both spoke for the agreement rather than failing to express their dissatisfaction at the need to resort to such an extreme solution.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has credited himself with the addition of an agreement on certain measures, in particular one aimed at enabling owners to maintain their residence, and of wage measures leading to the state of the saved firms' labor.
"When we ask the taxpayers to take special measures because of the irresponsibility of some people, there is nothing to congratulate themselves on.
However, these measures are necessary, "he explained on the waves of television.
His Republican opponent, John McCain, who was questioned by another station to vote in favour of the proposed plan, replied, "I'd like to see the details, but I hope so."
"The rough features that I have read [show] that this is something that we will all have to digest and with which it will be possible to move forward.
It is simply unacceptable to choose inaction, "he said.
The aim of the 700 billion plan is to buy back the dues' dubious debts and risky and unsold assets of US financial institutions.
The plan comes after 14 months of the crisis unleashed by the collapse of the real estate bubble, which first led to the collapse of risky mortgage loans (subprimes), then transferred to other, more widespread forms of credit (PCAA) and resulted in the freezing of cash and the decomposition of banks and financial institutions.
The fall in the first draft agreement of last week is the result of Republican Members.
Since the Democrats agreed that some "toxic" assets of companies in difficulty will only be guaranteed by the government, but not bought, there is a belief that the impasse is over.
In an attempt to bring the conflicting views of Congress closer together, a measure has been introduced providing that the government will be able to introduce new charges to help it recover its contribution if it has to take on losses for five years as a result of the programme.
The new plan provides for a deposit of the first amount of 250 billion, to which it will be possible to add another 100 billion if the President considers it necessary.
The deposit of another 350 billion should be approved by Congress in a new vote.
In exchange for his help, Washington will acquire shares in the rescue companies that will pay dividends to him in the event of profits, and which will be able to sell again when this is over.
The Federal Government will be able to delay the foreclosure procedures related to the loans to which the plan relates, as well as to set limits on the amount of evaluation and compensation paid to the managers of the firms affected.
The leaders of the plan would like to put it to the vote in the House of Representatives today and in the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all the efforts that have been made, it is not yet certain that their plan will have a green light.
Yesterday, voices continued to rise against this project both in the Republican and in the democratic camp.
"It is clear that Washington cannot hear you," said Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the Financial Commission of the House.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But making money on taxpayers is not the answer. "
Democratic representative Brad Sherman, host of a group of congressmen called the "sceptics committee," presents the whole thing differently, but the same conclusion is reached.
"Four hundred esteemed economics professors, among them three Nobel laureates, wrote to us: we ask Congress not to rush too fast and carefully explore which way to go," he said yesterday.
At the same time, it was reaffirmed in Europe that this crisis is a global crisis.
At the end of the extraordinary meeting, three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalisation of the Fortis banking group for EUR 11.2 billion (USD 16.3 billion).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it was withdrawing from the purchase of its competitor, which has been on the verge of collapse since it lost EUR 2 billion (USD 2,9 billion) as a result of the crisis in risk loans for the purchase of real estate in the United States.
Fortis employs 85 000 people, among the twenty largest European banks and among the ten largest insurers.
"We will not lose this money," said the Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos yesterday.
"In return, we gain the right to vote in the bank and influence.
That is what savers and households at times of uncertainty can appreciate. "
On the other side of the Channel La Manche, the British government seems to have started nationalizing another bank affected by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government was to take over all existing loans from Bradford and Bringley, of which more than 41 billion (USD 75.5 billion) were loans for the purchase of real estate.
According to his announcement yesterday, the Spanish bank Santander will buy out the branches and accounts of British bank clients.
Bradford and Bringley will be the second bank after Northern Rock to be nationalized by the British government since the beginning of the financial crisis.
