Soon, on 8 October, a trial against János Zuschlag and his associates will begin.
In addition to other crimes, including forgery, the politician and his associates are accused of fraud committed by a long-term and systematic criminal organisation which has caused extremely significant damage.
According to the prosecution, they used the money obtained in public competitions for their own purposes and often documented the performance of their tasks through fictitious invoices.
The money from the state and the government - roughly 65 million forints in total - went partly to the Treasury of Fiatal Baloldal, partly to the individual pockets.
The way it also informed the investigating office was that the money obtained in the public tenders was collected on the basis of invoices for which there was no real consideration and the association's commitments were never received.
According to the prosecution, a large proportion of the invoices were false.
Forms for these invoices came from the Yózsefváros market, round stamps were produced in Kiskunhalasi.
The names of which companies the production of invoices was to take place were decided, among other things, on a tour along the north bank of Balaton, on which István Lados János Zuschlag sent.
According to his testimony, the first-named was supposed to be looking at guesthouses and restaurants.
In them he applied for accounts for his consumption, according to which the invoices submitted in the context of the competitions, including the Ministry of Youth and Sport, the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs and the Authority of the Capital, were subsequently produced.
The invoices were mostly exhibited by István Lados with his partner András, the one who, according to our information, wrote the most frequent reports needed to obtain subsidies.
On his "study trip," Lados saw a beer house.
According to two invoices issued by Zuschlag and his associates in 2003, this catering facility provided catering for a 90-member group from Biztos Pont.
But so many people, according to the company manager, wouldn't be able to fit into this facility at once.
