Psychology of trumping: why are we spending more money?
In auctions, customers are willing to spend more money, overestimate goods.
Neurological and economic foundations of this famous - and seemingly irrational - behavior have been revealed to researchers in the field of neurology and economics of the University of New York.
According to their study, published in Science magazine, the people in the eBay auction contest don't want to fall behind, so they'd rather pay a price too high.
Research was using an experimental auction to try to map the pattern of this "game" in the nervous system.
One group of volunteers was betting, the other group participated in the played auction, with the use of the functional magnetic resonance (fMRI) method being investigated in the active regions of the brain of the test subjects.
In both games, participants could win money, but when playing at an auction, the important element of which is to top the other side, a whole under the cerebral cortex, called the striatum, began to work intensively in the losing.
In addition to many other functions, this brain region plays a role in the "self-rewarding" mechanism of the nervous system.
Thus, according to researchers, it is possible to explain how to avoid the sharp reaction of the striata.
To support their theory, members of the economist research team conducted a cross-cutting financial investigation.
Under different circumstances, three groups regretted one partner.
The control group was simply told what the real value of the product was, and they made bets.
In addition, members of the next group were promised that if they came out of the game victorious, they would still get $15 for the reward.
On the contrary, the third group received $15 before the auction, but in the event of a loss, its members lost this money as well.
The difference between the two groups was therefore all in all that one was emphasized by the win and the other by the loss.
But the members of the anti-loss group were willing to go higher than in the control and "winning" group, which confirms the neurologist hypothesis.
"These results cannot be derived from any previously existing economic theory.
These have so far explained the phenomena observable in the auctions of the joy of victory and avoiding risk.
Until the neurological imaging methods helped us solve the contradiction between these two theories by now having come to a third explanation, "said Andrew Schotter, Professor of the New York University Economic Faculty.
Hepatitis: when to find a doctor?
Approximately half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infection, and in Hungary, this chronic liver disease is reported among the main causes of death.
The number of domestic cases of hepatitis infection is estimated to be 100,000, but only seven thousand of them are being treated.
The name hepatitis is a cumulative name for infectious liver damage caused by various viruses.
There are many similarities in their symptoms, including inflammation of the liver and jaundice, but the causes of the disease and the diseases they cause differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses are spread in two main ways depending on the underlying disease: hepatitis A and E through the digestive system (for example, infected food, water), hepatitis B, C, D, and other viruses by blood and body fluids (sperm, vaginal secretions, saliva).
Travelers should in any case be protected by vaccination against virus A and B, there is no vaccine against virus C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A occur two to three weeks after ingestion of an infected meal, usually accompanied by nausea, weakness, abdominal discomfort, nausea.
Thereafter, jaundice, light stools and darkens urine appear on the skin and on the whites of the eyes. The treatment may take two to three weeks.
Every year, a million people around the world die of a more serious type of disease, liver cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main cause is that, according to estimates, only every tenth infected person is treated medically.
Also hepatitis C can have very serious consequences: if it is not treated, it can lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most of the infected do not even know the disease agent is destroying liver cells maliciously, so the first symptoms will occur in many cases in 20-30 years.
This is why early prevention, the implementation of regular depistation is very important.
In three groups, this disease occurs much more frequently than on average: among people who had a blood transfusion before 1991, between drug users and people with tattoos.
Currently, the estimated global number of individuals infected with chronic hepatitis C virus is 200 million.
As the disease can demonstrate a routine laboratory examination, a person should contact his / her general practitioner if he / she has noticed any sign of unknown origin.
In early detection, the disease is treatable, the virus can be removed from the body to prevent the infection and prevent cancer.
September 30 is the world's Hepatitis Day, which was organized for the first time by organisations representing the sick worldwide in 2004.
Its aim is to draw attention to the chronic inflammation of the liver caused by these viruses, the causes of its formation and the importance of early detection of the disease.
Who believes in God doesn't hurt so much?
According to recent research, faith in God works as a certain analgesic that could facilitate the death of Catholic martyrs.
Scientists from Oxford University conducted an interesting experiment, examining how the belief in the God of the perception of pain affects man, informed the British journal Telegraph.
As part of a rather bizarre survey, 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists were subjected to electric shocks while all observed the painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to rule out much of the pain.
Thanks to a technique that closely examines the human brain, it has also been shown that Catholics have been able to activate the part of their brain that is responsible for controlling pain.
Research is the first of a series of research that scientists, philosophers and theologians from different parts of the university take part in alongside academics.
The exact test was carried out by attaching to the left hand of the test subject a sparkle instrument that produced electric shocks.
The researchers asked the participants to observe two paintings: the Sassaferrat Virgin Mary, dating back to the 17th century, and the Lady with Leonard da Vinci's French fries, painted in the 15th century.
The authors of the research hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary would bring about a certain state of piety for the believers, while Da Vinci's painting was chosen because they were not very different from the first and they found it to be a soothing impression.
The test subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner and during that time they received 20 electric shocks in four consecutive parts, while they separately watched the painting with a religious or general theme.
Catholics said that when they looked at the Virgin Mary, they felt "safe" as if they were "taken care of" and "calmed down, they were filled with peace."
When watching a religious painting, they felt 12 percent less pain than when they had Leonard's work in front of them.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the research, believes that a similar effect can be achieved through any powerful image even for atheists, only to find the right photo.
"We would have to find an image that they would perceive very positively, from the position of mother or father," said the psychologist.
The Bishop of England, Tom Wright, welcomed the results of the research.
"The practice of faith should change and in many cases it will change our personality," said Wright.
After such excellent results, it is only a question of what effect it would have on regulating the pain of believers if they had shown them some Madonna from Leonard or a painter of similar caliber.
Would a look at the quality of the Virgin Mary mean achieving even better results?
