Intelligent car imitates bumblebee flight
What would be the best method of developing technologies capable of preventing collision, if not imitation of obstacle detectors occurring in the world of nature?
Bees, for example.
The initial strategic idea of the surprise project presented at the Japanese CEATEC fair was inspired by engineers from Nissan bumblebees. It was about building a new generation of systems to prevent collisions.
In cooperation with the University of Tokyo, Nissan designed a biomimetic robotic control system of the BR23C type, a robotic mini car equipped with bee properties, with the ultimate aim of helping to create a system that can eliminate all rainfall.
"During the flight, each bee creates its own personal space of oval shape, which is actually very similar to our safety cover," explained Kazuhiro Doi, CEO of the brand for technological PR and research and development.
Folded eyes play an important role, allowing bees to see more than 300 degrees in all directions.
To copy the function of the folded eye, engineers reached after the idea of a laser remote meter.
It identifies obstacles up to 2 metres ahead of BR23C in a 180-degree field of vision, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor that is immediately transformed into an operation to prevent collision.
The obstacle is captured within a fraction of a second, then the robotic car starts to imitate the movements of the bee and by turning the wheels to the extent necessary to prevent the collision, it immediately changes direction.
Unlike any existing system, this evasive maneuver is going on in an entirely instinctive way.
"If this had not been the case, a robotic car would not have been able to react fast enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshijuki Ando, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotic car project.
It must respond instinctively and immediately, as this technology meets the most vulnerable and intrinsic layer of safety-cover, which is currently considered inevitable by the collision.
The whole process must reflect what a bee does to avoid other bees.
This process must not take longer than the blink of an eye.
However, unlike bees, this movement cannot be directed upwards, downwards or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and only in the direction in which the wheels can be turned.
Instead of the endless possibilities offered to bees when avoiding, in the case of a robotic car, only the possibility of rotating movement, acceleration and deceleration was applied.
BR23C uses lithium polymer accumulators that are lighter and have higher energy density, which means they have a longer lifetime than lithium ion variants.
According to Ando, an instinctive, intelligent response is important, not a processing ability, the less data storage.
This mechanism shall only process and react to several incoming signals per second.
There is no need for him to store them and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, so he is still using only a few kilobytes of memory.
It doesn't need memory with giga- or megabyte capacity.
This is the first step towards developing an immediate avoidance technology that is estimated by Nissan to reach mass-produced vehicles within ten years.
Another possibility of application can be the connection of the unit with the GPS satellite navigation system, which would lead the motorist to the final destination after avoiding obstacles.
Damn dear child already has a name
The $700 billion economy package bill, which is to be split into several instalments and which aims to buy out poor bank loans, is already in writing.
In the first round, half the amount will be used.
After further negotiations, which ended on Saturday after midnight American Eastern Time, Congress officials reached an agreement in a few days' debate on a $700 billion rescue package, Reuters told us.
"We have made significant progress," said Nancy Pelosi, the Democratic President of the House of Representatives, according to which only the drafting of the agreement remains.
The compromise on the package was also supported by both presidential candidates Barack Obama and John McCain.
Finance Minister Henry Paulson said about the outcome of the compromise: "The programme will work and will be effective, but further action needs to be taken."
The written form of the package was published before the opening of Asian markets on Sunday at 8: 00 p.m. Washington time (i.e. on Monday at 2: 00 a.m. Central European time), but it did not cause any special rise on the stock exchanges.
On Monday, the House of Representatives will vote first, and then the Senate will have its turn on the draft law hearing the name of the 2008 Emergency Economic Stabilisation Act to be established.
President George W. Bush spoke to Pelosi on Saturday night, then they also welcomed the news of the agreement at the White House.
"We are satisfied with the progress made at night and we very much appreciate both parties' efforts to stabilise our financial markets and protect our economy," said White House spokesman Tony Fratto.
Indeed, the programme is different from the Bush administration's original proposal, in which it was intended to spend a total of $700 billion on the purchase of poor mortgage-backed securities.
It is now possible to spend up to half the amount of 700 billion in the first round, by using 250 billion immediately after the Congress decides on Monday, and by purchasing mortgage-backed securities that are classified as poor, the fate of the remaining $100 billion will depend on the president's decision.
The programme will be controlled by a special corps, a member of which will also be the chairman of the Federal Reserve Bank.
The spending of the second half of $700 billion will depend on the next decision of Congress.
The Ministry of Finance may apply a combined tactic under the law: it may at the same time purchase low-quality loans, mortgages and mortgage-backed securities, or other "toxic" loans.
The buy-out can take place both directly and directly, communicated by the competent representatives of the Ministry.
The legal standard will allow the companies concerned to participate in an insurance scheme in which the Ministry of Finance will provide them with a guarantee of funds that provide cause for concern, for which the company will pay the price corresponding to the amount of the expected damage.
As Henry Paulson said, the law provides the necessary resources to spend as much as $700 billion to meet the urgent demands of the US financial system, whether it be large-scale purchases of bad funds, insurance, or to prevent systemic risks associated with the collapse of one of the major monetary institutions.
"We will take the necessary steps to be prepared to implement the law as soon as it is signed," he added.
On the contrary, bank bosses who are in trouble waiting to help the state can count on the government to reduce their severance - which is simply called a "golden parachute" in overseas slang.
They will only be restricted in certain cases, and these restrictions will depend on the way the Ministry provides assistance.
In essence, the restriction means that if the Ministry buys under the auction, a tax surcharge will be imposed on gold parachutes if the fallen directors of banks are not sent straight to retirement.
In the event of a direct buy-in of low-quality loans, the government will aggressively intervene in order to ensure that the money for management is not excessive.
It must be added that already existing gold parachute contracts will not change, the restriction concerns only new ones, which is intended to further stimulate participation in the programme.
"This is the first case in American history where there will be a legal restriction on the remuneration of the Directors-General," said the President of the Committee on the Financial Services of the House of Representatives, Democrat Barney Frank.
In addition, the right of the State in the banks participating in the programme to acquire a stake will fall, reducing the risk of taxpayers, because once the economy and the bank that is saved are on their feet, they can also make money on this transaction.
The draft plan states that in the next five years, the President must submit to Congress a proposal setting out how the expected losses from the financial sector can be repaid to taxpayers.
There were, of course, voices expressing doubts about the plan on both sides.
"This is not what American citizens have asked us to do, because this will not protect taxpayers' dollars," said the Republican congressman from California Darrell Issa.
His democratic colleague from Ohio, Mary Kapturo, believes that it was those responsible for Wall Street's collapse who insisted on adopting the provisions.
Industrial prices continued to increase
In August 2008, domestic sales prices in the industry increased by 0.1% in relation to the previous month, by 12.9% compared to August 2007, reported by the Central Statistical Office.
Export sales prices in the industry were higher by 1.1% compared to July 2008 and decreased year-on-year by 3.9%.
Production prices in industry were higher by 0.7 percent as a result of changes in domestic and export prices compared to the previous month, increasing by 3.2% year-on-year.
The domestic sales prices in the industry increased by a minimum of 0.1% in relation to the previous month.
The domestic sales prices in the manufacturing industry also increased slightly, by 0.1%, compared to July.
The largest price increase took place in the leather and footwear industry in August 2008 (2.8%), mainly due to the monthly price increase in the bag and saddler products industry by 4.6%, respectively, and the production of footwear by 2.5%.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical raw materials has caused a significant monthly price increase in chemical materials and products production (1,6%).
Prices decreased in the oil processing sector (1,4%), production of electrical machinery and equipment (0,9%), as well as - to a minimum - in the woodworking sector (0,1%).
Prices in paper production and publishing and printing activities have not changed.
In other sectors of the manufacturing industry, we measured a price increase of between 0.2% and 0.9%.
In the electricity, gas and water sector, which has a high weight in domestic sales of the industry, prices increased by 0.3% in August, mainly the continuing effect of the official increase in gas prices since 1 July.
In a 12-month comparison of domestic sales in individual manufacturing industries, prices increased most in the oil processing industry (32.4 percent).
In the metal production sector, 13.2% could be observed, with 11% price increases in the production of food products, beverages and tobacco products, which have a decisive weight.
Prices were reduced in the textile and textile production sectors (2.5%) and in the production of electrical machinery and apparatus (0.3%).
In other sectors of the manufacturing industry, the rate of price increase ranged between 0.6% and 9.1%.
Overall, prices in the manufacturing industry increased by 10.2% over the last year.
Prices in the electricity, gas and water sectors exceeded the prices of the previous year by 18.7%.
In August, the highest monthly price increase (0,7%) in the sectors concerned with the production of tangible assets was reflected in the sector's division according to the focus of the sector.
In the consumer goods sector, prices increased by 0.3%, in the energy processing and further processing sectors, prices did not change in relation to the previous month.
In August 2008, the largest price increase in terms of the same month of the previous year could be observed in the energy processing and further processing sectors (16.8%).
In the consumer goods sector, we measured a price increase of 6.8%, while in the case of tangible assets, we measured a price decrease of 1.4%.
Export sales prices of industrial products measured in forints increased by 1.1% in August compared to the previous month, falling by 3.9% in the 12-month comparison.
In one month, our domestic tender has weakened by 1.7 percent in relation to the euro, by 7.1 percent in relation to the dollar, by 7.5 percent in relation to the euro compared to August 2007, and by 15.9 percent in relation to the dollar.
